<h1 class="heading" align="center"> Leave Policy </h1>

<h3>1. Objective</h3>
<p>Recognizing that employees may need time away from work for personal tasks, medical
reasons or annual vacations, JOSH SOFTWARE provides employees with leave under
various categories, governed by the policies outlined below.</p>
<h3> 2. Advance Notice </h3>
<p>Employees will be responsible for planning and organizing every type of leave with their
project managers and team members ahead of time, keeping the needs of ongoing work in
mind. Managers will thereupon approve applications for leave submitted by the employee
as defined below.</p>
<h3>3. Leave Year</h3>
<p>The leave year is the calendar year (January to December).</p>
<h3> 4. Types of Leave</h3>
<p>Employees may be eligible for the following categories of leave:
  <ol>
    <li> Privilege Leave </li>
    <li> Casual Leave </li>
    <li> Sick Leave </li>
    <li> Maternity Leave </li>
    <li> Paternity Leave </li>
  </ol>
</p>
<h3>5. Leave Approval </h3>
<ul>
<li> Employees are eligible for all types of leave from the day they join. Leave will
accrue to them at the end of every pay period on a pro-rata basis.</li>
<li> Employees must apply for leave using a prescribed leave request form. These are
available with the Human Resource department</li>
<li> An employee must apply for leave to his/her Manager, or Consultant or Director in
case the Manager is not available.</li>
<li> The Manager will approve an employee's leave after considering the workload,
schedules, essentiality of leave in case of multiple applications, and any other
relevant factors apart from the availability of leave.</li>
<li> Leave can be taken only after the Manager or an appropriate manager has
approved the leave.</li>
</ul>
<p>In case of unanticipated or sick leave, employees should make reasonable efforts to inform
their Manager, project team or administrative personnel as soon as possible.</p>

<h3>6. Privilege Leave </h3>

<p>The following policies apply to privilege leave:
  <ul>
    <li> Employees will be eligible for a maximum of 19 (nineteen) days of privilege leave in a leave year. For employees joining in the middle of the year, privilege leave is
    credited on a pro-rata basis from the joining date of the employee.</li>
    <li> Privilege leave not taken in a leave year can be carried forward to the next leave
    year, up to a maximum of 15 days.</li>
    <li> Weekends or published holidays during the leave period will not be counted as part
    of privilege leave.</li>
  </ul>
</p>
<h3>7. Casual Leave</h3>
<p>The following applies to casual leave:
  <ul>
    <li> Employees are eligible for 6 (six) days of casual leave in a leave year. For
    employees joining in the middle of the year, casual leave is credited on a pro-rata
    basis from the joining date of the employee.</li>
    <li> As with all other leave categories, employees must make every attempt to get
    casual leave pre-approved. Should that not prove possible, employees must inform
    Managers.</li>
    <li> Casual leave cannot be taken for more than 2 consecutive working days</li>
    <li> Casual leave can be prefixed and/or suffixed with either weekends or published
    holidays. In such cases, the total period of absence shall not exceed 4 days at a
    stretch. Intervening holidays during the leave period will not be included in the count
    of casual leave days.</li>
    <li> Casual leave cannot be combined with other types of leave.</li>
    <li> Casual leave can be taken in 1/2 day increments.</li>
  </ul>
</p>
<h3>8. Sick Leave</h3>
<p>Each employee of the company is eligible for sick leave for reasons of ill health. The
following applies to sick leave:
  <ul>
    <li> Employees are eligible for 6 (six) days of sick leave in a leave year and this is
    credited in advance at the beginning of the leave year.</li>
    <li> Sick leave taken for more than 2 consecutive days must be supported by a medical
    certificate from a registered medical practitioner.</li>
    <li> Sick leave can be prefixed and/or suffixed with either weekends or published
    holidays. Intervening holidays during the leave period will not be calculated as part
    of sick leave.</li>
  </ul>
    As with all other leave categories, employees must make every attempt to inform
  Managers.
</p>

<h3> 9. Maternity Leave</h3>
<p>
The company is governed by the Maternity Benefit Act, 1961. All married female
employees not covered under the Employee's State Insurance Act, 1948 are eligible for
benefits under the Act. They may take paid maternity leave for a maximum of 12 weeks i.e.
6 weeks prior to and including the date of delivery, and 6 weeks following that date up to 2
children only, in accordance with Maternity Benefit Act. The following applies to maternity
leave:
  <ul>
    <li> Only female employees who have completed a minimum of 1 year of service in the
    company are eligible for maternity leave.</li>
    <li> The employee must provide a certificate from her doctor verifying the pregnancy.</li>
    <li> The maternity leave may be extended without pay with prior approval, on
    production of a medical certificate. Employees do not earn privilege, casual and
    sick leave during extensions and privilege, casual and sick leave is adjusted against
    the required period of leave extension.</li>
  </ul>
</p>
<h3>10. Paternity Leave </h3>
<p>All married male employees are eligible for paternity leave. The following applies to
paternity leave:
  <ul>
    <li> Eligible employees may take paternity leave for a maximum of 3 days within 30
    days of delivery.</li>
    <li> Paternity leave can be prefixed and/or suffixed with weekends and/or published
    holidays.</li>
    <li> Paternity leave may be extended without pay with prior approval. Employees do not
    earn privilege, casual and sick leave during the extension period and privilege,
    casual and sick leave is adjusted against the required period of extension.</li>
  </ul>
</p>
<h3>11. Leave Encashment</h3>
<p>
The company allows employees to receive cash for part of their accrued privilege leave as
follows:
  <ul>
    <li> Privilege leave that cannot be carried over to the next year will be automatically
    encashed.</li>
    <li> A minimum privilege leave balance of 10 days must be available after privilege
    leave encashment</li>
    <li> The employee must make a request for encashment in the format specified by the
    Human Resource department</li>
    <li> Encashment will be subject to taxation, and will be calculated as follows - (Current
    Gross Salary) x (No. of days being cashed)/365</li>
    <li> The value of cash received would be added to the employee's salary for purposes
    of computation of income and other taxes</li>
  </ul>
</p>

<h3>12. Leave without Pay (LWOP) </h3>
<ul>
<li> Leave without pay is discouraged except in special circumstances.</li>
<li> The salary (excluding any reimbursements) of an employee going on LWOP for that
month will be reduced proportionately for the days of LWOP.</li>
<li> In case an employee is absent from work without prior approval or when the
application for leave has not been approved, such an absence will also be treated
as LWOP. Depending on the circumstances, such absence may attract disciplinary
action.</li>
</ul>
<h3>13. Calculation of Leave on Separation</h3>
<p>In the event of separation of the employee from the Company, all the leave credited to the
employee till the date of separation from the company would be encashed as per the
calculations described above.</p>
<h3>14.  Modification / Change in policy</h3>
<p>Management reserves the right to modify / change the above policy as deemed appropriate
from time to time.</p>

